This is one of the larger 
<taxonomicName id="4C554D537B20FFBFFBBCF9F4FB85DE2D" authorityName="Scudder" authorityYear="1872" box="[1040,1147,1572,1595]" class="Insecta" family="Nymphalidae" genus="Speyeria" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="17" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B921EAC27B20FFBFFBBCF9F4FB85DE2D" box="[1040,1147,1572,1595]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="17">Speyeria</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
with pointed forewings. Adult wingspan ranges from 
<quantity id="4CAD9B357B20FFBFFD8DF993FD60DE4D" box="[545,670,1603,1627]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="6.8" metricValueMax="8.5" metricValueMin="5.1" pageId="18" pageNumber="17" unit="mm" value="68.0" valueMax="85.0" valueMin="51.0">51-85 mm</quantity>
. The dorsal wing surface in both sexes is bright tawny and dark markings are moderate except along the margin where they are well marked with chevrons that point toward the wing base. The ventral forewings are bright pinkish orange at base and shading to yellow toward the distal margin with the same black pattern as upper side. The ventral hindwings bear oval or elongate silver spots and the disc is mottled with a dull greenish olive coloration. There are no subspecific names associated with 
<taxonomicName id="4C554D537B20FFBFFE4DF934FD83DEED" box="[481,637,1763,1787]" class="Insecta" family="Nymphalidae" genus="Argynnis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="17" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="edwardsii">
<emphasis id="B921EAC27B20FFBFFE4DF934FD83DEED" box="[481,637,1763,1787]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="17">S. edwardsii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and there is little wing variation throughout its range. 
<taxonomicName id="4C554D537B20FFBFFA99F934FEDCDF0D" baseAuthorityName="Boisduval" baseAuthorityYear="1852" class="Insecta" family="Nymphalidae" genus="Speyeria" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="17" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="callippe">
<emphasis id="B921EAC27B20FFBFFA99F934FEDCDF0D" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="17">Speyeria callippe</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
may be superficially similar in appearance where their ranges overlap, but 
<taxonomicName id="4C554D537B20FFBFFB7EF8D4FAABDF0D" baseAuthorityName="Boisduval" baseAuthorityYear="1852" box="[1234,1365,1795,1819]" class="Insecta" family="Nymphalidae" genus="Speyeria" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="17" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="callippe">
<emphasis id="B921EAC27B20FFBFFB7EF8D4FB1ADF0D" box="[1234,1252,1796,1819]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="17">S</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis id="B921EAC27B20FFBFFB5FF8D3FAABDF0D" box="[1267,1365,1795,1819]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="17">callippe</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
bears ventral hindwing marginal spots that are more pointed rather than rounded inwardly as they appear on 
<taxonomicName id="4C554D537B20FFBFFF6CF894FEA6DF4D" box="[192,344,1859,1883]" class="Insecta" family="Nymphalidae" genus="Argynnis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="17" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="edwardsii">
<emphasis id="B921EAC27B20FFBFFF6CF894FEA6DF4D" box="[192,344,1859,1883]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="17">S. edwardsii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. 
<bibRefCitation id="EFC44B217B20FFBFFEC9F893FDC9DF4D" author="Hammond, P. C." box="[357,567,1859,1883]" pageId="18" pageNumber="17" pagination="54 - 76" refId="ref40109" refString="Hammond, P. C. 1990. Patterns of geographic variation and evolution in polytypic butterflies. Journal of Research on the Lepidoptera 29: 54 - 76." type="journal article" year="1990">Hammond (1990)</bibRefCitation>
hypothesized that 
<taxonomicName id="4C554D537B20FFBFFCB0F894FC4ADF4D" box="[796,948,1859,1883]" class="Insecta" family="Nymphalidae" genus="Argynnis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="17" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="edwardsii">
<emphasis id="B921EAC27B20FFBFFCB0F894FC4ADF4D" box="[796,948,1859,1883]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="17">S. edwardsii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
may have evolved directly from 
<taxonomicName id="4C554D537B20FFBFFA9AF894FD93DF6D" authority="(McDunnough)" baseAuthorityName="McDunnough" class="Insecta" family="Nymphalidae" genus="Speyeria" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="17" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subSpecies" species="callippe" subSpecies="semivirida">
<emphasis id="B921EAC27B20FFBFFA9AF894FE53DF6D" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="17">Speyeria callippe semivirida</emphasis>
(McDunnough)
</taxonomicName>
(but see 
<bibRefCitation id="EFC44B217B20FFBFFD75F8B3FC66DF6D" author="Scott, J. A." box="[729,920,1891,1915]" pageId="18" pageNumber="17" pagination="1 - 129" refId="ref45004" refString="Scott, J. A. 2008 a. Corrections / reviews of 58 North American butterfly books. Papilio 19: 1 - 129." type="journal article" year="2008">Scott 2008a: 80</bibRefCitation>
). 
<taxonomicName id="4C554D537B20FFBFFC07F8B4FB8BDF6D" baseAuthorityName="Behr" baseAuthorityYear="1864" box="[939,1141,1892,1915]" class="Insecta" family="Nymphalidae" genus="Speyeria" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="17" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="coronis">
<emphasis id="B921EAC27B20FFBFFC07F8B4FB8BDF6D" box="[939,1141,1892,1915]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="17">Speyeria coronis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is also similar but bears large, round median spots on the hindwing disc. The uncus on the male genitalia is clawed and slender, unlike the previous 5 species discussed above. The digitus (
<figureCitation id="136E2A557B21FFBEFC25FF33FBFBD8ED" box="[905,1029,227,251]" captionStart="Figure 4" captionStartId="11.[194,278,1029,1051]" captionTargetBox="[194,1442,193,998]" captionTargetId="figure-357@11.[194,1442,193,998]" captionTargetPageId="11" captionText="Figure 4. Male genitalic armature. A) Speyeria idalia (locality unknown). B) Speyeria cybele (Nebraska). C) Speyeria hesperis (aedeagus removed) (Idaho). D) Digitus located on left valva, Speyeria edwardsii (Nebraska). Images by James C. Dunford." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5352668" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5352668/files/figure.png" pageId="19" pageNumber="18">Figure 4D</figureCitation>
) on each valva is long and slender and unlike any other member in the genus (others have more or less a short, club-like digitus). Eggs are greenish yellow and generally shaped like the rest of 
<taxonomicName id="4C554D537B21FFBEFC9FFEF4FC62D92D" authorityName="Scudder" authorityYear="1872" box="[819,924,292,315]" class="Insecta" family="Nymphalidae" genus="Speyeria" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="19" pageNumber="18" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B921EAC27B21FFBEFC9FFEF4FC62D92D" box="[819,924,292,315]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="18">Speyeria</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Larvae are dark yellow dorsally, with gray laterally and a black dorsal stripe. The upper four rows of spines are gray at the base; the lower two rows of spines are orange at the base. The pupa is approximately 
<quantity id="4CAD9B357B21FFBEFC0EFEB3FC09D96D" box="[930,1015,355,379]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.2" pageId="19" pageNumber="18" unit="mm" value="22.0">22 mm</quantity>
in length and brown with anterior portions reddish in color. The wing cases are yellow-brown with dark streaks along the veins. Detailed egg, larval instar, and pupal descriptions are included in 
<bibRefCitation id="EFC44B217B21FFBEFCC2FE73FBBED9AD" author="Edwards, W. H." box="[878,1088,419,443]" pageId="19" pageNumber="18" pagination="3 - 5" refId="ref36961" refString="Edwards, W. H. 1888 b. Description of the preparatory stages of Argynnis edwardsii, Reakirt. The Canadian Entomologist 20: 3 - 5." type="journal article" year="1888">Edwards (1888b)</bibRefCitation>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BEA36D07B21FFBEFF6CFE33FBCCDA2D" blockId="19.[192,1440,483,571]" pageId="19" pageNumber="18">
<emphasis id="B921EAC27B21FFBEFF6CFE33FEDED9ED" bold="true" box="[192,288,483,507]" pageId="19" pageNumber="18">Range.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="4C554D537B21FFBEFE89FE34FDF1D9ED" box="[293,527,483,507]" class="Insecta" family="Nymphalidae" genus="Speyeria" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="19" pageNumber="18" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="edwardsii">
<emphasis id="B921EAC27B21FFBEFE89FE34FDF1D9ED" box="[293,527,483,507]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="18">Speyeria edwardsii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is known from southern 
<collectingRegion id="4991F8327B21FFBEFC96FE33FC69D9ED" box="[826,919,483,507]" country="Canada" name="Alberta" pageId="19" pageNumber="18">Alberta</collectingRegion>
east to 
<collectingRegion id="4991F8327B21FFBEFC5FFE33FB92D9ED" box="[1011,1132,483,507]" country="Canada" name="Manitoba" pageId="19" pageNumber="18">Manitoba</collectingRegion>
, south through the Dakotas, western 
<collectingRegion id="4991F8327B21FFBEFEF7FDD3FE2DDA0D" box="[347,467,515,539]" country="United States of America" name="Nebraska" pageId="19" pageNumber="18">Nebraska</collectingRegion>
and 
<collectingRegion id="4991F8327B21FFBEFDA1FDD3FD6EDA0D" box="[525,656,515,539]" country="United States of America" name="Oklahoma" pageId="19" pageNumber="18">Oklahoma</collectingRegion>
, and west to northern 
<collectingRegion id="4991F8327B21FFBEFC32FDD4FBC9DA0D" box="[926,1079,515,539]" country="United States of America" name="New Mexico" pageId="19" pageNumber="18">New Mexico</collectingRegion>
. They are seldom found above 
<quantity id="4CAD9B357B21FFBEFF6CFDF3FED5DA2D" box="[192,299,547,571]" metricMagnitude="0" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.048" pageId="19" pageNumber="18" unit="ft" value="10.0">10,000 ft</quantity>
in 
<collectingRegion id="4991F8327B21FFBEFEE3FDF3FE3FDA2D" box="[335,449,547,571]" country="United States of America" name="Colorado" pageId="19" pageNumber="18">Colorado</collectingRegion>
. Stray records also exist in 
<collectingRegion id="4991F8327B21FFBEFCA6FDF4FC98DA2D" box="[778,870,548,571]" country="United States of America" name="Kansas" pageId="19" pageNumber="18">Kansas</collectingRegion>
(
<bibRefCitation id="EFC44B217B21FFBEFCD8FDF3FBDBDA2D" author="Ely, C. A. &amp; M. E. Rolfs &amp; T. E. Labedz" box="[884,1061,547,571]" pageId="19" pageNumber="18" pagination="256 - 257" refId="ref37241" refString="Ely, C. A., M. E. Rolfs, and T. E. Labedz. 1983. New and unusual butterfly records from Kansas. Journal of the Lepidopterists' Society 37: 256 - 257." type="journal article" year="1983">Ely et al. 1983</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BEA36D07B21FFBEFF6CFDB3FCABDB4D" blockId="19.[192,1441,611,859]" pageId="19" pageNumber="18">
<emphasis id="B921EAC27B21FFBEFF6CFDB3FE99DA6D" bold="true" box="[192,359,611,635]" pageId="19" pageNumber="18">Life history.</emphasis>
Habitat includes short grass prairie, foothills, meadows, glades, open pine forests, valleys and roadsides. Individuals are known to migrate into the mountains during the midsummer months with females moving back into the prairies during the late summer to lay eggs (
<bibRefCitation id="EFC44B217B21FFBEFB82FD73FABBDAAD" author="Opler, P. A. &amp; A. B. Wright" box="[1070,1349,675,699]" pageId="19" pageNumber="18" refId="ref43436" refString="Opler, P. A., and A. B. Wright. 1999. A field guide to Western butterflies. Second edition. Houghton Mifflin Company; Boston, Massachusetts. 540 p." type="book" year="1999">Opler and Wright 1999</bibRefCitation>
). Males will patrol for females all day in open areas regardless of topography (
<bibRefCitation id="EFC44B217B21FFBEFBABFD13FB75DACD" author="Scott, J. A." box="[1031,1163,707,731]" pageId="19" pageNumber="18" pagination="1 - 40" refId="ref44669" refString="Scott, J. A. 1975. Mate-locating behavior of western North American butterflies. Journal of Research on the Lepidoptera 14: 1 - 40." type="journal article" year="1975">Scott 1975</bibRefCitation>
). Flight period extends from mid-May through late October. 
<bibRefCitation id="EFC44B217B21FFBEFDDAFD33FCBCDAED" author="Edwards, W. H." box="[630,834,739,763]" pageId="19" pageNumber="18" pagination="3 - 5" refId="ref36961" refString="Edwards, W. H. 1888 b. Description of the preparatory stages of Argynnis edwardsii, Reakirt. The Canadian Entomologist 20: 3 - 5." type="journal article" year="1888">Edwards (1888b)</bibRefCitation>
noted the egg stage is approximately 10 to 11 days. Larvae, which pass through five molts after overwintering as a first instar, feed for approximately 45 days before pupating. The duration of the pupal stage is approximately 15 days. 
<bibRefCitation id="EFC44B217B21FFBEFB0FFCF3FABEDB2D" author="Scott, J. A." box="[1187,1344,803,827]" pageId="19" pageNumber="18" pagination="1 - 37" refId="ref44779" refString="Scott, J. A. 1986 a. Larval hostplant records for butterflies and skippers (mainly from western U. S.), with notes on their natural history. Papilio 4: 1 - 37." type="journal article" year="1986">
Scott (1986 
<bibRefCitation id="EFC44B217B21FFBEFA9EFCF3FABEDB2D" author="Scott, J. A." box="[1330,1344,803,827]" pageId="19" pageNumber="18" pagination="1 - 74" refId="ref44961" refString="Scott, J. A. 2006 b. Butterfly hostplant records, 1992 - 2005, with a treatise on the evolution of Erynnis, and a note on new terminology for mate-collecting behavior. Papilio 14: 1 - 74." type="journal article" year="2006">a</bibRefCitation>
</bibRefCitation>
, 2006b) reports various oviposition substrates for 
<taxonomicName id="4C554D537B21FFBEFD1AFC94FCB0DB4D" box="[694,846,835,859]" class="Insecta" family="Nymphalidae" genus="Speyeria" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="19" pageNumber="18" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="edwardsii">
<emphasis id="B921EAC27B21FFBEFD1AFC94FCB0DB4D" box="[694,846,835,859]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="18">S. edwardsii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
